    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      I joined Facebook as a Product Design Intern on the Business Design Systems Team in the summer of 2019.
      <p>In my final week, I worked on a bonus project– designing placeholders for 'empty' media items.
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
      <strong>Creating an empty state for media items</strong><br><br>
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      <strong>The Problem</strong><br><br>
      There is no empty state for media items! <br><br>
      Let's look at a list of Facebook posts with thumbnails of images uploaded for each ad. If the post creator did not upload an image for the most recent post, they see a blank media item container.<br><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-facebook/current.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="The current empty state for media items"><br>
      The blank thumbnail can easily be misinterpreted as: <br>
      1. An image that's still loading, <br>
      2. An image that's simply lost, or <br>
      3. A broken image (server side failure) <br>
      when, in fact, <p class="channel-orange"> it's none of the above!</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      <strong>The Goal</strong><br><br>
      How might we use iconography to signify an empty media item (no image uploaded)?<br><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-facebook/exploration.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="An exploration by Mariano, Product Design Intern on PACE Team"><br>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths text-center">
    <br><br><br><strong>An exploration by Mariano, Product Design Intern on PACE Team</strong><br><br>
    Mariano came to our team with his empty state explorations for his use case.<br>
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      The empty state icon Mariano suggested made sense; however, its generic look suggested clickability, as if clicking on the thumbnail would allow the user to upload an image for the entity.<br><br>
      Ad creators should click on the post title, where they can view a post's details in full, to upload an image for the Facebook post. Prompting the user to upload an image isn't always the case either as posts can be text-only.<br><br>
      With this constraint, I had to design an empty state for entities (like an ad posting or a business) that <p class="channel-orange"> serves as a placeholder and nothing more.</p><br><br>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths text-center">
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      <strong>My Process</strong><br><br>
      I did a quick search to find iconography that's conventionally used as placeholders for images–<br><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-facebook/null.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Mountain + sun iconography conventionally used as placeholders for media items"> <br><br><br>
       To start, I looked through some of their illustration assets to get a better sense of their color palette and illustration style.<br><br>
      I stumbled upon an illustration with the familiar mountain + sun combo sitting on the interface.<br><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-facebook/interface.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="An illustration by the IPB4B Team"> <br><br>
      I explored how it can be simplified to live in a 48 x 48px thumbnail.<br><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-facebook/simplify.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Mountain + sun iconography conventionally used as placeholders for media items">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths case-image">
      <br><br>Images of the mountain + sun combo surfaced. I decided to adopt this since I wanted the iconography to be familiar enough to speak for itself. But I had to style it.<br><br>
      I worked closely with the In-Product Branding for Business (IPB4B) Team from the get-go to keep my visual style consistent with the illustrations and animations across our products.</p>
    </div>
  </div><br><br>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      I picked out my top 2 designs and mocked them up onto the table to see how they fare in context.<br><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-facebook/feedback.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Mountain + sun iconography conventionally used as placeholders for media items"><br><br>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths text-center">
      I presented these options at my team crit where a designer suggested that I apply neutral colors to the icon so that it falls back into the surface instead of calling attention to itself. The last thing we wanted was to confuse the creator into thinking that they unintentionally uploaded an image.<br><br>
    </div>
  </div><br>

