    <div class="col-md-2-5ths">
      <strong>Next Steps</strong><br><br>
      1. Schedule 1:1s with interested faculty members to discuss opportunities for integrating screening and  interviewing into the Janus workflow.<br><br>
      2. Synthesize insights from the focus groups and interviews for the next iteration.<br><br><br>
      <strong>Some Things I Learned</strong><br><br>
      1. It’s practical to build by component.<br>
      For the student and admin sides, I could reuse (and possibly expand) the design system I had already created to unify all three ends under the same umbrella platform.<br><br>
      2. Anticipate interactions among all three ends.<br>
      Keeping the color-coded workflow in mind, even while designing for just one stakeholder at a time, enabled me to identify features that facilitated end-to-end data transmission and communication.<br><br>
      3. Seek out feedback by organizing feedback sessions.<br>
      Feedback is the most powerful driver of my design decisions– whether it involves backtracking to a previous solution/decision or testing a range of hypotheses.<br><br>
      4. There is always someone I can serve better.<br>
      It pays to go out of my way to get to know users, their habits and behaviors in person if I want to accommodate as many kinds of people as possible– tech geeks, busy bees, disabled users, etc.
    </div>
